{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606025"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:07:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:07:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15889"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15889"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.27,0.23,0.04,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72053"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8580"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15889"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57523"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8595"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20572"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72053"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe placental barrier separates maternal and fetal circulation while allowing exchange of nutrients, gases and waste products. The structure of this barrier changes throughout pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key structural change that occurs in the placental barrier at 15 weeks of pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cytotrophoblast layer becomes discontinuous","Syncytiotrophoblast layer disappears","Fetal endothelial cells first appear","Connective tissue layer thickens","Maternal blood spaces form"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early pregnancy, the placental barrier consists of four main layers: \u003Cstrong\u003Ecytotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esyncytiotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Econnective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Efetal endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E. Around week 15, the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecytotrophoblast layer becomes discontinuous\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a normal part of placental maturation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis structural change helps reduce the distance between maternal and fetal circulation, making exchange of nutrients and gases more efficient. The syncytiotrophoblast layer remains intact throughout pregnancy, and the fetal endothelial cells are present from early development. The connective tissue actually becomes thinner, not thicker, as pregnancy progresses. Maternal blood spaces develop much earlier, during implantation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The placental barrier consists of syncytiotrophoblast, cytotrophoblast, connective tissue, and fetal endothelial cells in early pregnancy","By week 15, the cytotrophoblast layer becomes discontinuous as part of normal placental maturation","The final placental barrier consists mainly of syncytiotrophoblast and fetal endothelial cells"],"references":["Kojima J, Ono M, Kuji N, Nishi H. Human Chorionic Villous Differentiation and Placental Development. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Jul 20;23(14):8003. doi: 10.3390/ijms23148003. PMID: 35887349; PMCID: PMC9325306","Jones TM, Montero FJ. Chorionic Villus Sampling. [Updated 2022 Dec 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563301/","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57523"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15889"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57523"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:06:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:07:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8580"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72053"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"desc